2 NEW SECTION. Section 2. Electric facilities provider -- wildfire -- wildfire mitigation plan
3 approval. (1) An electric facilities provider may prepare a wildfire mitigation plan in accordance with this
4 section.
5 (2) A wildfire mitigation plan must include a description of:
6 (a) areas in which the electric facilities provider has electric facilities or electric transmission and
7 distribution activities that may be subject to a heightened risk of wildfire;
8 (b) the strategies and programs that the electric facilities provider will use to inspect and operate
9 its electric facilities;
10 (c) the strategies and programs that the electric facilities provider will use to perform vegetation
11 management;
12 (d) the strategies for modifications or upgrades to electric facilities and preventative programs that
13 the electric facilities provider may employ to reduce the risk of its electric facilities igniting a wildfire;
14 (e) the strategies and methods for de-energizing power lines and modifying electric facility
15 operations to mitigate potential wildfires taking into consideration the ability of the electric facilities provider to
16 reasonably access the proposed electric facility to be de-energized, the balance of the risk of wildfire with the
17 need for continued supply of electricity to a community, and any potential impact to public safety, first
18 responders, and health and communications infrastructure;
19 (f) the methods the electric facilities provider intends to use to restore its electrical system in the
20 event systems are de-energized for the prevention of a wildfire;
21 (g) the estimated incremental costs associated with implementing the plan, including system
22 improvements and upgrades for a regulated utility;
23 (h) community outreach and public awareness efforts before and during a wildfire season; and
24 (i) potential participation, if applicable, with state or local wildland fire protection plans or wildfire
25 mitigation plans.
26 (3) An electric cooperative must present incremental costs associated with implementing a wildfire
27 mitigation plan to its board of trustees for consideration when reviewing the plan; however, those costs may not
28 be a part of the wildfire mitigation plan itself.
