11 recovery is sought.
12 (4) In an action against an electric facilities provider seeking wildfire-related damages arising from
13 the electric facilities provider's electric facilities or electric transmission and distribution activities, there is a
14 rebuttable presumption that the electric facilities provider acted reasonably if the electric facilities provider has
15 adopted and, with respect to the place of the wildfire's ignition, substantially followed a wildfire mitigation plan
16 that contains at a minimum the elements in [section 2(2)], provided that evidence related to the electric facilities
17 provider's actual incremental costs associated with implementing a wildfire mitigation plan may not be
18 considered in determining whether the electric facilities provider substantially followed its wildfire mitigation
19 plan. The presumption in this subsection (4) may be controverted by other evidence.
20 (5) In an action against an electric facilities provider seeking wildfire-related damages arising from
21 the electric facilities provider's electric facilities or electric transmission and distribution activities, the absence of
22 a wildfire mitigation plan may not be construed as evidence of or an inference that the electric facilities provider
23 did not meet the standard in subsection (3)(a), and the fact finder may consider only acts that may have caused
24 the wildfire's ignition and evaluate the electric facilities provider's acts and electric transmission and distribution
25 activities in the context of the electric facilities provider's overall systems, processes, and programs.
26 (6) In an action against an electric facilities provider under this section, if a plaintiff has proved
